{{refimprove|date=July 2015}}

'''Aperiodic frequency''' is the [[rate (mathematics)|rate]] of incidence or occurrence of non-[[Periodic function|cyclic]] phenomena, including random processes such as [[radioactive decay]]. It is expressed in [[units of measurement]] of [[reciprocal seconds]] (s<sup>−1</sup>)<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.ro/books?id=3UGQsi6VamwC&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage&q&f=false|title=Mechatronic Systems, Sensors, and Actuators: Fundamentals and Modeling|last=Lombardi|first=Michael A.|date=2017-07-28|publisher=CRC Press|year=2007|isbn=9781420009002|editor-last=Bishop|editor-first=Robert H.|location=Austin|pages=18-1|language=en|chapter=Fundamentals of Time and Frequency}}</ref> or, in the case of radioactivity, [[becquerels]].<ref>{{Cite journal|last=|first=|date=2014|title=Units with special names and symbols; units that incorporate special names and symbols|url=https://www.bipm.org/en/publications/si-brochure/section2-2-2.html|journal=SI Brochure: The International System of Units (SI)|edition=8th|volume=Section 2.2.2|pages=|via=|Section=}}</ref> 

It is defined as a [[ratio]], ''f'' = ''N''/''T'', involving the number of times an [[Event (philosophy)|event]] happened (''N'') during a given time [[Time|duration]] (''T''); it is a [[physical quantity]] of type [[temporal rate]].

