'''Dorothée Le Maître''' ({{IPA-fr|dɔʁɔte lə mɛtʁ|-|Fr-Dorothée Le Maître.ogg}}; 1 September 1896 – 26 January 1990) was a French [[Paleontology|paleontologist]] known for her studies of [[Devonian]] flora and fauna in [[North Africa]] and [[Sub-Saharan Africa]].
== Early life and education == Le Maître was educated at [[Angers Free University]] and received her bachelor's degree from the [[Catholic University of Lille]] in 1926. She remained there for her doctoral studies and earned her Ph.D. in 1934.<ref name=":0">{{Cite book|title = The Biographical Dictionary of Women in Science: L-Z|url = https://books.google.com/books?id=LTSYePZvSXYC|publisher = Taylor & Francis|date = 2000-01-01|isbn = 9780415920407|first = Marilyn Bailey|last = Ogilvie|first2 = Joy Dorothy|last2 = Harvey}}</ref>
== Career and research == Her first paper was published in 1926, the same year she earned her bachelor's degree. After her Ph.D., Le Maître became a faculty member at the [[University of Lille]], where she was a geology researcher. Her research included work on the ''[[Spongiomorphides]]'' and included comparative research of North African and Sub-Saharan fossils to those of Europe.<ref name=":0" />
== Honors and awards == In 1941, Le Maître was awarded the [[Prix Fontannes]], and in 1956 she received the [[Kuhlmann Prize]]. In 1959, she was honored by the [[French Academy of Sciences]] with the Grand Prix Bonnet. She was the president of the Société Géologique du Nord in 1949.<ref name=":0" />
