[[File:Tomb of Nakht (13).jpg|thumb|upright=1.35|[[Grape]]s being trodden to extract the juice and [[Fermentation in food processing|fermented]] to [[wine]] in storage jars. Tomb of [[Nakht]], [[18th dynasty]], [[Thebes, Egypt|Thebes]], [[Ancient Egypt]]]] {{good article}} '''Human interactions with microbes''' include both practical and symbolic uses of [[microbe]]s, and negative interactions in the form of human, domestic animal, and crop diseases.
Practical use of microbes began in ancient times with [[fermentation in food processing]]; [[bread]], [[beer]] and [[wine]] have been produced by [[yeast]]s from the dawn of civilisation, such as in [[ancient Egypt]]. More recently, microbes have been used in activities from [[biological warfare]] to the production of chemicals by fermentation, as industrial chemists discover how to manufacture a widening variety of organic chemicals including [[enzyme]]s and bioactive molecules such as [[hormone]]s and [[competitive inhibition|competitive inhibitors]] for use as medicines. Fermentation is used, too, to produce substitutes for fossil fuels in forms such as [[ethanol]] and [[methane]]; [[Algae fuel|fuels may also be produced by algae]]. Anaerobic microorganisms are important in [[sewage treatment]]. In scientific research, yeasts and the bacterium ''[[Escherichia coli]]'' serve as [[model organism]]s especially in [[genetics]] and related fields.
On the symbolic side, an early poem about brewing is the [[Sumer]]ian "Hymn to [[Ninkasi]]", from 1800 BC. In the [[Middle Ages]], [[Giovanni Boccaccio]]'s ''[[The Decameron]]'' and [[Geoffrey Chaucer]]'s ''[[The Canterbury Tales]]'': addressed people's fear of deadly contagion and the moral decline that could result. Novelists have exploited the [[Apocalyptic and post-apocalyptic fiction|apocalyptic possibilities]] of [[pandemic]]s from [[Mary Shelley]]'s 1826 ''[[The Last Man]]'' and [[Jack London]]'s 1912 ''[[The Scarlet Plague]]'' onwards. [[Hilaire Belloc]] wrote a humorous poem to "The Microbe" in 1912. Dramatic plagues and mass infection have formed the story lines of many [[Hollywood]] films, starting with ''[[Nosferatu]]'' in 1922. In 1971, ''[[The Andromeda Strain]]'' told the tale of an [[extraterrestrial life|extraterrestrial microbe]] threatening life on Earth. [[Microbiologist]]s since [[Alexander Fleming]] have used coloured or [[fluorescence|fluorescing]] colonies of bacteria to create miniature artworks.
Microorganisms such as [[bacteria]] and [[virus]]es are important as [[pathogen]]s, causing disease to humans, [[crop plant]]s, and [[domestic animal]]s.
==Context== [[File:Bakermiddleages.jpg|thumb|upright|Calendar from a Medieval [[book of hours]]: the month of December, showing a [[baking|baker]] putting [[bread]] into the oven. c. 1490–1500]] {{further|Microorganism}}
[[Culture]] consists of the [[social behaviour]] and [[Norm (social)|norms]] found in [[human]] [[society|societies]] and transmitted through social [[learning]]. [[Cultural universals]] in all human societies include expressive forms like [[art]], [[music]], [[dance]], [[ritual]], [[religion]], and [[technology|technologies]] like [[tool|tool usage]], [[cooking]], [[shelter (building)|shelter]], and [[clothing]]. The concept of [[material culture]] covers physical expressions such as technology, architecture and art, whereas immaterial culture includes principles of [[social organization]], [[mythology]], [[philosophy]], [[literature]], and [[science]].<ref name=MacionisGerber2011>{{cite book |url=https://www.worldcat.org/title/sociology/oclc/652430995 |title=Sociology |last=Macionis |first=John J. |last2=Gerber |first2=Linda Marie |date=2011 |publisher=Pearson Prentice Hall |isbn=978-0137001613 |page=53 |accessdate=29 May 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170818045455/https://www.worldcat.org/title/sociology/oclc/652430995 |archivedate=18 August 2017 |dead-url=no}}</ref> This article describes the roles played by microorganisms in human culture.
Since microbes were not known until the [[Early Modern]] period, they appear in earlier literature indirectly, through descriptions of [[baking]] and [[brewing]]. Only with the invention of the [[microscope]], as used by [[Robert Hooke]] in his 1665 book ''[[Micrographia]]'',<ref>{{cite book |last1=Hooke |first1=Robert|title=Micrographia: Or Some Physiological Descriptions of Minute Bodies Made by Magnifying Glasses, with Observations and Inquiries Thereupon |date=1665 |publisher=Courier Dover |isbn=0-486-49564-7 |url=https://books.google.com/?id=0DYXk_9XX38C&pg=PA113&lpg=PA113&dq=Micrographia+honeycomb#v=onepage&q=Micrographia%20honeycomb&f=false|accessdate=22 July 2014}}</ref> and by [[Antonie Van Leeuwenhoek]] in the 1670s,<ref>{{cite book |author=Payne, A.S. |title=The Cleere Observer: A Biography of Antoni Van Leeuwenhoek |page=13 |publisher=Macmillan |date=1970}}</ref> the [[germ theory of disease]], and progress in [[microbiology]] in the 19th century were microbes observed directly, identified as living organisms, and put to use on a scientific basis.<ref>{{cite web|title=Germ Theory|url=http://science.jrank.org/pages/3035/Germ-Theory.html|publisher=Rank|accessdate=27 September 2016}}</ref> The same knowledge also allowed microbes to appear explicitly in literature and the arts.<ref>{{cite web|title=Menagerie of Microbes|url=http://www.ascus.org.uk/exhibitions/menagerie-of-microbes/|publisher=Ascus|accessdate=27 September 2016|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160927162641/http://www.ascus.org.uk/exhibitions/menagerie-of-microbes/|archivedate=27 September 2016}}</ref>
==Practical uses== [[File:The Brewer designed and engraved in the Sixteenth. Century by J Amman.png|upright|thumb|A 16th-century brewery, engraved by [[Jost Amman]]]]
===Food production=== {{Main|Fermentation in food processing}}
Controlled [[Fermentation (food)|fermentation]] with microbes in [[brewing]], [[wine making]], [[baking]], [[pickling]] and cultured [[dairy product]]s such as [[yogurt]] and [[cheese]], is used to modify ingredients to make [[foods]] with desirable properties. The [[List of microorganisms used in food and beverage preparation|principal microbes involved]] are [[yeast]]s, in the case of beer, wine, and ordinary [[bread]]; and [[bacteria]], in the case of [[anaerobic respiration|anaerobically]] fermented [[vegetable]]s, [[dairy product]]s, and [[sourdough]] bread. The cultures variously provide flavour and aroma, inhibit pathogens, increase digestibility and palatability, make bread rise, reduce cooking time, and create useful products including [[alcohol]], [[organic acid]]s, [[vitamin]]s, [[amino acid]]s, and [[carbon dioxide]]. Safety is maintained with the help of [[food microbiology]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.foodsci.uoguelph.ca/dairyedu/micro.html |title= Dairy Microbiology |accessdate=9 October 2006 |publisher= University of Guelph}}</ref><ref name=Steinkraus>{{cite book |editor=Steinkraus, K. H. |date=1995 |title=Handbook of Indigenous Fermented Foods |publisher=Marcel Dekker}}</ref><ref name="HuiMeunier-Goddik2004">{{cite book |last1=Hui |first1=Y. H.|last2=Meunier-Goddik |first2=Lisbeth |last3=Josephsen |first3=Jytte |first4=Wai-Kit |last4=Nip |first5=Peggy S. |last5=Stanfield |title=Handbook of Food and Beverage Fermentation Technology |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=PC_O7u1NPZEC&pg=PA27 |year=2004 |publisher=CRC Press |isbn=978-0-8247-5122-7 |pages=27 and passim}}</ref>
===Water treatment=== {{Main|Sewage treatment}} Oxidative sewage treatment processes rely on microorganisms to oxidise organic constituents. Anaerobic microorganisms reduce sludge solids producing [[methane]] gas and a sterile mineralised residue. In [[potable water]] treatment, one method, the [[slow sand filter]], employs a complex gelatinous layer composed of a wide range of microorganisms to remove both dissolved and particulate material from raw water.<ref>{{Cite book| title=Biology of Wastewater Treatment | author=Gray, N.F. | publisher=Imperial College Press | year=2004 | page=1164 | isbn=1-86094-332-2}}</ref>
===Energy=== {{Main|Algae fuel|Cellulosic ethanol|Ethanol fermentation}}
Microorganisms are used in fermentation to produce ethanol,<ref>{{Cite book| title=Biomass Handbook |author1=Kitani, Osumu |author2=Carl W. Hall | publisher=Taylor & Francis US | year=1989 | page=256 | isbn=2-88124-269-3}}</ref> and in [[biogas]] reactors to produce methane.<ref>{{Cite book| title=Food, Energy, and Society | author=Pimental, David | publisher=CRC Press | year=2007 | page=289 | isbn=1-4200-4667-5 }}</ref> Scientists are researching the use of [[algae fuel|algae to produce liquid fuels]],<ref>{{Cite book| title=From the Fryer to the Fuel Tank: The Complete Guide to Using Vegetable Oil as an Alternative Fuel | author=Tickell, Joshua| publisher=Biodiesel America | year=2000 | page=53 | isbn=0-9707227-0-2|display-authors=etal}}</ref> and bacteria to convert various forms of agricultural and urban waste into [[cellulosic ethanol|usable fuels]].<ref>{{Cite book| title=Apollo's Fire: Igniting America's Clean Energy Economy | author=Inslee, Jay| publisher=Island Press | year=2008 | page=157 | isbn=1-59726-175-0|display-authors=etal}}</ref>
===Chemicals, enzymes === [[File:Penicillin bioreactor.jpg|thumb|An early [[Penicillin]] bioreactor, from 1957, now in the [[Science Museum, London]]]] {{main|Industrial enzymes}}
Microorganisms are used for many commercial and industrial purposes, including the production of chemicals, [[enzymes]] and other bioactive molecules, often through [[protein engineering]]. For example, [[acetic acid]] is produced by the bacterium ''[[Acetobacter aceti]]'', while [[citric acid]] is produced by the fungus ''[[Aspergillus niger]]''. Microorganisms are used to prepare a widening range of bioactive molecules and enzymes. For example, [[Streptokinase]] produced by the bacterium ''[[Streptococcus]]'' and modified by [[genetic engineering]] is used [[clot buster|to remove clots]] from the blood vessels of patients who have suffered a [[myocardial infarctions|heart attack]]. [[Cyclosporin A]] is an [[immunosuppressive agent]] in [[organ transplantation]], while [[statins]] produced by the yeast ''[[Monascus purpureus]]'' serve as [[blood cholesterol]] lowering agents, [[competitive inhibition|competitively inhibiting]] the enzyme that synthesizes cholesterol.<ref>{{cite book |title=Biology textbook for class XII |publisher=National council of educational research and training |isbn=81-7450-639-X |page=183}}</ref>
===Science=== Microorganisms are essential tools in [[biotechnology]], [[biochemistry]], [[genetics]], and [[molecular biology]]. The yeasts brewer's yeast (''[[Saccharomyces cerevisiae]]'') and fission yeast (''[[Schizosaccharomyces pombe]]'') are important [[model organism]]s in science, since they are simple [[eukaryote]]s that can be grown rapidly in large numbers and are easily manipulated.<ref>{{Cite journal |author=Castrillo J.I.; Oliver S. G. |title=Yeast as a touchstone in post-genomic research: strategies for integrative analysis in functional genomics |journal=J. Biochem. Mol. Biol. |volume=37 |issue=1 |pages=93–106 |year=2004 |pmid=14761307 |url=http://www.jbmb.or.kr/fulltext/jbmb/view.php?vol=37&page=93 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080615044016/http://www.jbmb.or.kr/fulltext/jbmb/view.php?vol=37&page=93 |dead-url=yes |archive-date=2008-06-15 |doi=10.5483/BMBRep.2004.37.1.093 }}</ref> They are particularly valuable in genetics, [[genomics]] and [[proteomics]], for example in [[protein production]].<ref>{{Cite journal |author=Suter, B.; Auerbach, D.; Stagljar, I. |title=Yeast-based functional genomics and proteomics technologies: the first 15 years and beyond |journal=BioTechniques |volume=40 |issue=5 |pages=625–44 |year=2006 |pmid=16708762 |doi=10.2144/000112151}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|author=Sunnerhagen, P. |title=Prospects for functional genomics in Schizosaccharomyces pombe |journal=Curr. Genet. |volume=42 |issue=2 |pages=73–84 |year=2002 |pmid=12478386 |doi=10.1007/s00294-002-0335-6}}</ref><ref>{{cite book| title=Microbes: A Source of Energy for 21st Century| author=Soni, S. K. | publisher=New India Publishing | year=2007 | isbn=81-89422-14-6}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book| title=Biotechnology: The Science and the Business | author=Moses, Vivian | publisher=CRC Press | year=1999 | page=563 | isbn=90-5702-407-1|display-authors=etal}}</ref> The easily cultured gut bacterium ''[[Escherichia coli]]'', a [[prokaryote]], is similarly widely used as a model organism.<ref name=lee1996>{{cite journal | author=Lee, S. Y. | title=High cell-density culture of Escherichia coli | journal=Trends in Biotechnology | volume=14 | issue=3 | pages=98–105 | date=March 1996 | pmid=8867291 | doi=10.1016/0167-7799(96)80930-9 }}</ref>
[[File:B-w-scientists.jpg|thumb|Scientists working with Class III cabinets at the U.S. Biological Warfare Laboratories, Camp Detrick, Maryland, in the 1940s]]
===Endosymbiosis=== {{further|Human microbiota}}
Microbes can form an [[Endosymbiont|endosymbiotic]] relationship with larger organisms. For example, the bacteria that live within the human digestive system [[Human flora#Human bacterial flora and human health|contribute to human health]] through gut immunity, the synthesis of [[vitamin]]s such as [[folic acid]] and [[biotin]], and the fermentation of complex indigestible [[carbohydrate]]s.<ref>{{cite journal |author1=O'Hara, A. |author2=Shanahan, F. | title=The gut flora as a forgotten organ | journal=EMBO Rep | volume=7 | issue=7 | pages=688–93 | year=2006 | pmid=16819463 | doi=10.1038/sj.embor.7400731 | pmc=1500832}}</ref> Future drugs and food chemicals may need to be tested on the gut microbiota; it is already clear that [[probiotic]] supplements can promote health, and that gut microbes are affected by both diet and medicines.<ref name="Valdes Walter Segal Spector p=k2179">{{cite journal | last=Valdes | first=Ana M | last2=Walter | first2=Jens | last3=Segal | first3=Eran | last4=Spector | first4=Tim D | title=Role of the gut microbiota in nutrition and health | journal=BMJ | date=2018 | doi=10.1136/bmj.k2179 | page=k2179}}</ref>
===Warfare=== {{Main|Biological warfare}}
Pathogenic microbes, and [[toxin]]s that they produce, have been developed as possible agents of warfare.<ref>{{cite book |last=Wheelis |first=Mark |last2=Rózsa |first2=Lajos |last3=Dando |first3=Malcolm |title=Deadly Cultures: Biological Weapons Since 1945 |publisher =Harvard University Press |year=2006 |isbn=0-674-01699-8}}</ref> Crude forms of biological warfare have been practiced since antiquity.<ref>{{Cite book |last=Mayor |first=Adrienne |title=Greek Fire, Poison Arrows & Scorpion Bombs: Biological and Chemical Warfare in the Ancient World |publisher=Overlook Duckworth |location=Woodstock, N.Y. |year=2003 |isbn=978-1-58567-348-3}}</ref> In the 6th century BC, the [[Assyrian people|Assyrians]] poisoned enemy wells with a [[fungus]] said to render the enemy delirious. In 1346, the bodies of [[Mongol Empire|Mongol]] warriors of the [[Golden Horde]] who had died of plague were thrown over the walls of the besieged [[Crimean Peninsula|Crimea]]n city of [[Caffa|Kaffa]], possibly assisting the spread of the [[Black Death]] into Europe.<ref>{{Cite journal |url=https://www.cdc.gov/ncidod/EID/vol8no9/01-0536.htm |last=Wheelis |first=Mark |title=Biological warfare at the 1346 siege of Caffa |journal=Emerg Infect Dis |publisher=Center for Disease Control|year= 2002 |doi=10.3201/eid0809.010536 |volume=8 |issue=9 |pages=971–5 |pmid=12194776 |pmc=2732530}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal | last1=Barras | first1=Vincent | last2=Greub | first2=Gilbert | year=2014 | title=History of biological warfare and bioterrorism | url=| journal=Clinical Microbiology and Infection | volume=20 | issue=6| pages=497–502 | doi=10.1111/1469-0691.12706}}</ref><ref>Andrew G. Robertson, and Laura J. Robertson. "From asps to allegations: biological warfare in history," ''Military medicine'' (1995) 160#8 pp: 369–373.</ref><ref>Rakibul Hasan, "Biological Weapons: covert threats to Global Health Security." ''Asian Journal of Multidisciplinary Studies'' (2014) 2#9 p 38. [http://www.ajms.co.in/sites/ajms/index.php/ajms/article/viewFile/559/488 online] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141217124035/http://www.ajms.co.in/sites/ajms/index.php/ajms/article/viewFile/559/488 |date=2014-12-17 }}</ref> Advances in [[bacteriology]] in the 20th century increased the sophistication of possible [[bio-agent]]s in war. Biological sabotage—in the form of [[anthrax]] and [[glanders]]—was undertaken on behalf of the [[German Empire|Imperial German]] government during [[World War I]], with indifferent results.<ref>Koenig, Robert (2006), ''The Fourth Horseman: One Man's Secret Campaign to Fight the Great War in America'', PublicAffairs.</ref> In [[World War II]], Britain weaponised [[tularemia]], [[Anthrax disease|anthrax]], [[brucellosis]], and [[botulism]] toxins, but never used them.<ref>{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/?id=SoDwO-dl-i0C |title=Biological Agents, Volume 2 |last=Prasad |first=S.K. |year=2009 |publisher=Discovery Publishing House |page=36 |isbn=978-81-8356-381-9}}</ref> The USA similarly explored biological warfare agents,<ref>Covert, Norman M. (2000), [http://www.detrick.army.mil/cutting_edge/index.cfm?chapter=contents "A History of Fort Detrick, Maryland", 4th Edition: 2000.]</ref> developing anthrax spores, [[brucellosis]], and botulism toxins for possible military use.<ref>{{cite journal |title=Scientists and the history of biological weapons: A brief historical overview of the development of biological weapons in the twentieth century |pmc=1490304 |year=2006 |last1=Guillemi n|first1=J. |volume=7 |issue=Spec No |pages=S45–S49 |doi=10.1038/sj.embor.7400689 |journal=EMBO Reports |pmid=16819450}}</ref> Japan developed biological warfare agents, with the use of [[human experimentation|experiments on human prisoners]], and was about to use them when the war ended.<ref name=Williams1989>{{Cite book |title=Unit 731: Japan's Secret Biological Warfare in World War II |publisher=Free Press |year=1989 |isbn=0-02-935301-7|last1=Williams |first1=Peter |last2=Wallace |first2=David}}</ref><ref>Naomi Baumslag, ''Murderous Medicine: Nazi Doctors, Human Experimentation, and Typhus'', 2005, p.207</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.globalsecurity.org/wmd/intro/bio_plague.htm| title=Weapons of Mass Destruction: Plague as Biological Weapons Agent | publisher=GlobalSecurity.org| accessdate=21 December 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.npr.org/2011/04/25/135638924/where-to-find-the-worlds-most-wicked-bugs| author=Amy Stewart| title=Where To Find The World's Most 'Wicked Bugs': Fleas| publisher=National Public Radio| date=25 April 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.japantimes.co.jp/opinion/2001/06/05/commentary/world-commentary/the-trial-of-unit-731/| author=Russell Working| title=The trial of Unit 731| publisher=The Japan Times| date=5 June 2001}}</ref>
==Symbolic uses== {{see|Disease in fiction|Parasites in fiction}}
Being very small, and unknown until the invention of the [[microscope]], microbes do not feature directly in art or literature before [[Early Modern]] times (though they appear indirectly in works about brewing and baking), when [[Antonie van Leeuwenhoek]]<!--slight overlink, seems sensible here--> observed microbes in water in 1676; his results were soon confirmed by [[Robert Hooke]]<!--slight overlink, seems sensible here-->.<ref>{{cite web |title=Antonie van Leeuwenhoek (1632–1723) |url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/history/historic_figures/van_leeuwenhoek_antonie.shtml |publisher=BBC|accessdate=29 June 2016 |date=2014}}</ref> A few major diseases such as [[tuberculosis]] appear [[tuberculosis in popular culture|in literature, art, film, opera and music]].<ref name=McMasterUni>{{cite web |url=http://hsl.mcmaster.libguides.com/c.php?g=306775&p=2045587 |title=Pulmonary Tuberculosis/In Literature and Art| publisher=McMaster University History of Diseases |accessdate=9 June 2017}}</ref>
===In literature===
[[File:Famous fantastic mysteries 194902.jpg|thumb|left|upright|[[Jack London]]'s 1912 ''[[The Scarlet Plague]]'' was reprinted in the February 1949 issue of ''[[Famous Fantastic Mysteries]]'']]
The literary possibilities of [[Apocalyptic and post-apocalyptic fiction|post-apocalyptic stories]] about [[pandemic]]s (worldwide outbreaks of disease) have been explored in novels and films from [[Mary Shelley]]'s 1826 ''[[The Last Man]]'' and [[Jack London]]'s 1912 ''[[The Scarlet Plague]]'' onwards. Medieval writings that deal with plague include [[Giovanni Boccaccio]]'s ''[[The Decameron]]'' and [[Geoffrey Chaucer]]'s ''[[The Canterbury Tales]]'': both treat the people's fear of contagion and the resulting moral decline, as well as bodily death.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Riva |first1=Michele Augusto |last2=Benedetti |first2=Marta |last3=Cesana |first3=Giancarlo |title=Pandemic Fear and Literature: Observations from Jack London's 'The Scarlet Plague' [another dimension] |journal=Emerging Infectious Diseases |date=October 2014 |volume=20 |issue=10 |page=online |doi=10.3201/eid2010.130278 |url=http://wwwnc.cdc.gov/eid/article/20/10/13-0278_article}}</ref>
The making of beer has been celebrated in verse since the time of Ancient [[Sumeria]], c. 1800 BC, when the "Hymn to [[Ninkasi]]" was inscribed on a clay tablet. Ninkasi, [[tutelary goddess]] of beer, and daughter of the creator Enki and the "queen of the sacred lake" Ninki, "handles the [[dough]] and with a big shovel, mixing in a pit, the bappir with [date] honey,&nbsp;... waters the [[malt]] set on the ground,&nbsp;... soaks the malt in a jar,&nbsp;... spreads the cooked [[mash (beer)|mash]] on large reed mats, coolness overcomes,&nbsp;... holds with both hands the great sweet [[wort]], [[brewing]] it with honey".<ref>{{cite web |title=Discover the Oldest Beer Recipe in History From Ancient Sumeria, 1800 B.C. |url=http://www.openculture.com/2015/03/the-oldest-beer-recipe-in-history.html |publisher=Open Culture |accessdate=29 June 2016 |date=3 March 2015}}</ref>
Wine is a frequent topic in [[English literature]], from the spiced French and Italian "[[hippocras|ypocras]]", "[[claret|claree]]", and "[[Vernaccia|vernage]]" in Chaucer's ''[[The Merchant's Tale]]'' onwards. [[William Shakespeare]]'s [[Falstaff]] drank Spanish "[[sherry|sherris sack]]", in contrast to [[Sir Toby Belch]]'s preference for "[[sack (wine)|canary]]". Wine references in later centuries branch out to more winegrowing regions.<ref name="Harding2015">{{cite book |last=Harding |first=Julia |title=The Oxford Companion to Wine |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=0PHcCQAAQBAJ&pg=PA261 |year=2015 |publisher=Oxford University Press |isbn=978-0-19-870538-3 |pages=261–263}}</ref>
''The Microbe'' is a humorous 1912 poem by [[Hilaire Belloc]], starting with the lines "The microbe is so very small / You cannot make him out at all,/ But many sanguine people hope / To see him through a microscope.<ref>{{cite book |title=The Microbe |work=More Beasts for Worse Children |publisher=Duckworth |url=http://www.poetry-archive.com/b/the_microbe.html#7GyRGMfxsZCEPap6.99 |author=Belloc, Hilaire |authorlink=Hilaire Belloc |date=1912 |accessdate=29 June 2016}}</ref> ''[[Microbes and Man]]'' is an admired "classic"<ref name=Hogg>{{cite book |last=Hogg |first=Stuart |title=Essential Microbiology |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=8yRRtGJxP7YC&pg=PT497 |year=2013 |publisher=John Wiley & Sons |isbn=978-1-118-68814-4 |pages=497}}</ref> book, first published in 1969, by the "father figure of British microbiology"<ref name="legless">Cole, Jeffrey, A., "Legless pathogens: how bacterial physiology provides the key to understanding pathogenicity", The [[Fred Griffith]] Prize Lecture 2011, reprinted in ''Microbiology'', 2012 Jun; 158(6):1402-13. {{doi| 10.1099/mic.0.059048-0}}; [http://mic.sgmjournals.org/content/158/Pt_6/1402.full.pdf PDF]{{subscription required}}</ref><ref name="Cole, p. 1402">{{cite journal|doi=10.1099/mic.0.059048-0 | volume=158 | title=Legless pathogens: how bacterial physiology provides the key to understanding pathogenicity | journal=Microbiology | pages=1402–1413}}</ref> [[John Postgate (microbiologist)|John Postgate]] on the whole subject of microorganisms and their relationships with humans.<ref>{{cite book |author=Postgate, John |authorlink=John Postgate (microbiologist) |date=2000 |title=Microbes and Man |edition=4th |isbn=0-521-66579-5}}</ref>
===In film=== [[File:Nosferatuposter.jpg|thumb|upright|Poster for the 1922 film ''[[Nosferatu]]'', whose protagonist spreads the [[Black Death]]]]
Microbes feature in many highly dramatized films.<ref name="Wald2008">{{cite book |last=Wald |first=Priscilla |title=Contagious: Cultures, Carriers, and the Outbreak Narrative |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=O8F6JAZAImIC&pg=PA31 |year=2008 |publisher=Duke University Press |isbn=0-8223-4153-0 |pages=31–}}</ref><ref name=Hsu/> [[Hollywood]] was quick to exploit the possibilities of deadly disease, mass infection and drastic government reaction, starting as early as 1922 with ''[[Nosferatu]]'', in which a [[Dracula]]-like figure, [[Count Orlok]], sleeps in unhallowed ground contaminated with the [[Black Death]], which he brings with him wherever he goes. Another classic film, [[Ingmar Bergman]]'s 1957 ''[[The Seventh Seal]]'', deals with the plague theme very differently, with the [[grim reaper]] directly represented by an actor in a hood. More recently, the 1971 ''[[The Andromeda Strain (film)|The Andromeda Strain]]'', based on [[The Andromeda Strain|a novel]] by [[Michael Crichton]], portrayed an extraterrestrial microbe contaminating the Earth.<ref name=Hsu>{{cite web |last1=Hsu |first1=Jeremy |title=Germs on the Big Screen: 11 Infectious Movies |url=http://www.livescience.com/15982-infectious-disease-movies.html |publisher=Live Science |accessdate=29 June 2016 |date=9 September 2011}}</ref>
===In music===
"[[A Very Cellular Song]]," a song from the British [[psychedelic folk]] band [[The Incredible String Band]]'s 1968 album ''[[The Hangman's Beautiful Daughter]],'' is told partially from the point of view of an [[amoeba]], a [[protista]]n.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.metrolyrics.com/a-very-cellular-song-lyrics-incredible-string-band.html|title=A Very Cellular Song Lyrics |work=Metro Lyrics |accessdate=29 June 2016}}</ref>
===In art=== {{main|Microbial art}}
[[Microbial art]] is the creation of artworks by culturing bacteria, typically on [[agar plate]]s, to form desired patterns. These may be chosen to [[fluorescence|fluoresce]] under ultraviolet light in different colours.<ref name=Science2009>{{cite journal |editor-last=Torrice |editor-first=Michael |date=6 November 2009 |title=Petri Dish Artists |url=http://science.sciencemag.org/content/326/5954/777.2/tab-pdf |format=pdf |journal=Science |publisher=AAAS |volume=326 |issue=5954 |page=777 |doi=10.1126/science.326_777b |access-date=17 April 2018}}</ref> [[Alexander Fleming]], the discoverer of [[penicillin]], created "germ paintings" using different species of bacteria that were naturally pigmented in different colours.<ref name=Fleming>{{cite web| url=http://www.smithsonianmag.com/science-nature/Painting-With-Penicillin-Alexander-Flemings-Germ-Art.html |title=Painting With Penicillin: Alexander Fleming's Germ Art |author=Dunn, Rob |publisher=[[Smithsonian Institution]] |date=11 July 2010}}</ref>
An instance of a [[protist]] in an artwork is the artist [[Louise Bourgeois]]'s [[bronze]] sculpture ''Amoeba''. It has a white [[patina]] resembling plaster, and was designed in 1963–5, based on drawings of a pregnant woman's belly that she made as early as the 1940s. According to the [[Tate Gallery]], the work "is a roughly modelled organic form, its bulges and single opening suggesting a moving, living creature in the stages of evolution."<ref>{{cite web|title=Louise Bourgeois. Amoeba 1963–5, cast 1984|url=http://www.tate.org.uk/art/artworks/bourgeois-amoeba-t07780|publisher=[[Tate Gallery]]|accessdate=29 June 2016}}</ref>
<gallery widths=200px mode=nolines> File:Hassall - Microbes in Thames at Brentford and Hungerford.jpg|Microbes in the [[Thames]] at Brentford and Hungerford. [[Arthur Hill Hassall]], 1850 File:Bacteria - in the laboratory of a field hospital the London specialist and his assistant examine the contents of a test tube Art.IWMART2939.jpg|A British [[First World War]] microbiologist in his laboratory, examining a test tube of bacteria. Painted by [[James McBey]], 1917 File:The Soviet Union 1966 CPA 3306 stamp (Microbiology International Congress (24-30.07, Moscow). Emblem - Microscope and Moscow University. Bacteria and Viruses).png|The [[Soviet Union]] 1966 stamp for the Microbiology International Congress. Bacteria and viruses form the background. File:FPbeachTsien.jpg|Beach scene with live bacteria in a [[Petri dish]] [[gene expression|expressing]] different [[fluorescent protein]]s. [[Microbial art]] by Nathan Shaner, 2006 </gallery>
==Negative interactions==
===Disease=== {{main|Pathogen}}
Microorganisms are the causative agents ([[pathogen]]s) in many infectious diseases of humans and domestic animals. [[Pathogenic bacteria]] cause diseases such as [[bubonic plague|plague]], [[tuberculosis]] and [[anthrax]]. Protozoa cause diseases including [[malaria]], [[African trypanosomiasis|sleeping sickness]], [[dysentery]] and [[toxoplasmosis]]. Microscopic fungi cause diseases such as [[ringworm]], [[candidiasis]] and [[histoplasmosis]]. [[Pathogenic viruses]] cause diseases such as [[influenza]], [[yellow fever]] and [[AIDS]].<ref>{{cite book |author1=Alberts, B. |author2=Johnson, A. |author3=Lewis, J. |title=Molecular Biology of the Cell |edition=4th |publisher=Garland Science |date=2002 |section=Introduction to Pathogens |url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK26917/ |page=1}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.metapathogen.com | title=MetaPathogen | accessdate=15 January 2015 }}</ref>
[[File:Semper Augustus Tulip 17th century.jpg|thumb|upright|[[Tulip mania|Semper Augustus Tulip]], 17th century, owed its pattern to [[Tulip breaking virus|a virus]].]]
The practice of [[hygiene]] was created to prevent [[infection]] or [[food]] spoiling by eliminating microbes, especially bacteria, from the surroundings.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.who.int/topics/hygiene/en/ |title=Hygiene |accessdate=29 June 2016}}</ref>
===In agriculture and horticulture=== {{main|Plant pathology}}
Microorganisms including [[bacteria]],<ref>{{cite journal | title=Bacteria as Plant Pathogens | publisher=Cornell University | date=October 1948 | author=Burkholder | journal=Annual Review of Microbiology | doi=10.1146/annurev.mi.02.100148.002133 | volume=2 | pages=389–412 | pmid=18104350}}</ref><ref name=JacksonRW>{{cite book | author=Jackson RW (editor). | title=Plant Pathogenic Bacteria: Genomics and Molecular Biology | publisher=Caister Academic Press | year=2009 | isbn=978-1-904455-37-0}}</ref> fungi, and [[virus]]es are important as plant [[pathogen]]s, causing disease to [[crop plant]]s. Fungi cause serious crop diseases such as [[maize]] leaf rust, [[wheat]] stem rust, and powdery mildew. Bacteria cause plant diseases including leaf spot and crown galls. Viruses cause plant diseases such as leaf mosaic.<ref>{{cite book |author=Agrios, George N. |title=Plant Pathology |edition=3rd |publisher=Academic Press |date=1972}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Isleib |first1=Jim |title=Signs and symptoms of plant disease: Is it fungal, viral or bacterial? |url=http://msue.anr.msu.edu/news/signs_and_symptoms_of_plant_disease_is_it_fungal_viral_or_bacterial |publisher=Michigan State University |date=19 December 2012 |accessdate=28 September 2016}}</ref> The [[oomycete]] ''[[Phytophthora infestans]]'' causes potato blight, contributing to the [[Great Irish Famine]] of the 1840s.<ref>{{cite book |last=Kinealy |first=Christine |year=1994 |title=This Great Calamity |publisher=Gill & Macmillan |isbn=0-7171-1881-9 |pages=xv and passim}}</ref>
The [[tulip breaking virus]] played a role in the [[tulip mania]] of the [[Dutch Golden Age]]. The famous Semper Augustus tulip, in particular, owed its striking pattern to infection with the plant disease, a kind of [[mosaic virus]], making it the most expensive of all the tulip bulbs sold.<ref>{{cite book |title=Tulipomania: The Story of the World's Most Coveted Flower & the Extraordinary Passions It Aroused |author=Dash, Mike |date=2001 |publisher=Gollancz}}</ref>
