This is a list of '''important publications''' in [[geology]], organized by field.

Some reasons why a particular publication might be regarded as important:
*'''Topic creator''' &ndash; A publication that created a new topic
*'''Breakthrough''' &ndash; A publication that changed scientific knowledge significantly
*'''Influence''' &ndash; A publication which has significantly influenced the world or has had a massive impact on the teaching of geology.<!-- The text of this lead section was substituted into this page from [[Template:List of publications intro]]. --><!--An entry in this list should include citations for statements about the importance of the publication. Otherwise it may be challenged and removed.-->

Compilations of important publications can be found in [[List of important publications in geology#Further reading|Further reading]].

==Foundations==
*{{cite book|first=Nicolas|last=Steno|title=Dissertationis prodromus|date=1669|author-link=Nicolas Steno}}
::Established the following stratigraphical principles: [[law of superposition]], [[principle of original horizontality]], [[principle of lateral continuity]] and the [[principle of cross-cutting relationships]] 
*{{cite journal |first=James|last=Hutton|author-link=James Hutton |title=Theory of the Earth; or an Investigation of the Laws observable in the Composition, Dissolution, and Restoration of Land upon the Globe |journal=Transactions of the Royal Society of Edinburgh |volume=1 |number=2 |pages=209&ndash;304 |year=1788 |url=https://books.google.com/?id=RjYAAAAAQAAJ&printsec=frontcover&dq=%22theory+of+the+earth%22+hutton#v=onepage&q=%22theory%20of%20the%20earth%22%20hutton&f=false |doi=10.1017/s0080456800029227}}<ref name=Mather>{{harvnb|Mather|Mason|1967}}</ref>{{rp|92&ndash;100}}<ref>{{cite book|last1=Dean|first1=Dennis R.|title=James Hutton and the history of geology|date=1992|publisher=Cornell University Press|location=Ithaca|isbn=9780801426667|pages=30&ndash;83}}</ref>
::First publication to clearly articulate the principle of [[deep time]], and to recognize that rocks record the evidence of the past action of processes which still operate today. These ideas were to grow into the idea of [[Uniformitarianism]]. Hutton is widely regarded as the "Father of Modern Geology".

*{{cite book|last1=Playfair|first1=John|author-link=John Playfair |title=Illustrations of the Huttonian theory of the Earth|date=1802|publisher=Cadell and Davies|location=London|url=https://archive.org/details/NHM104643}}
::Hutton's book is widely regarded as unreadable, and may have remained obscure if not for this work by the brilliant prose stylist John Playfair.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Gould|first1=Stephen Jay|title=Time's arrow time's cycle : myth and metaphor in the discovery of geological time|date=2001|publisher=Harvard University Press|location=Cambridge, Mass|isbn=9780674891999|page=61|edition=11th print.}}</ref>

*{{cite book|title=Principles of Geology: being an attempt to explain the former changes of the Earth's surface, by reference to causes now in operation|volume=1|first=Charles |last=Lyell |author-link=Charles Lyell |publisher=John Murray |location=London |year=1830|title-link=Principles of Geology}}
*{{cite book|title='' ''|volume=2|first=Charles |last=Lyell |author-link=Charles Lyell|author-mask=1 |publisher=John Murray |location=London |year=1832}}
*{{cite book|title='' ''|volume=3|first=Charles |last=Lyell |author-link=Charles Lyell |author-mask=1 |publisher=John Murray |location=London |year=1833}}<ref name=Mather/>{{rp|263&ndash;273}}<ref>[http://www.esp.org/books/lyell/principles/facsimile/title3.html Online facsimile]</ref>
::The work's subtitle was "An Attempt to Explain the Former Changes of the Earth's Surface by Reference to Causes now in Operation", and this explains Lyell's impact on science: he was, along with the earlier [[John Playfair]], the major advocate of the then-controversial idea of [[Uniformitarianism (science)|uniformitarianism]], that the Earth was shaped entirely by slow-moving forces acting over a very long period of time. This was in contrast to [[catastrophism]], a geologic idea that went hand-in-hand with the [[age of the Earth]] suggested by [[Bible|biblical]] chronology. In various revised editions (twelve in all, through 1872), ''[[Principles of Geology]]'' was the most influential geological work in the middle of the 19th century, and did much to put geology on a modern footing. [[Charles Darwin]] frequently acknowledged his deep debt to this book.<ref>From the dedication in [[Second voyage of HMS Beagle|Voyage of the Beagle]]: TO CHARLES LYELL, ESQ., F.R.S.: This Second Edition Is Dedicated with Grateful Pleasure, As an Acknowledgment That the Chief Part of Whatever Scientific Merit This Journal and the Other Works of the Author May Possess, Has Been Derived from Studying the Well-Known and Admirable PRINCIPLES OF GEOLOGY."</ref>

