*Pohl, W.L., 2011. Economic Geology, Principles and Practice: Metals, Minerals, Coal and Hydrocarbons – an Introduction to Formation and Sustainable Exploitation of Mineral Deposits. 663 Pages, Wiley-Blackwell, Oxford. {{ISBN|978-1444336627}}

==Geochemistry==
*{{cite book|last1=Goldschmidt|first1=Victor|author-link=Victor Goldschmidt |title=Geochemische Verteilungsgesetze der elemente|year=1923–1938 |publisher=|location=|isbn=}}
::Laid the foundations of [[geochemistry]], including the [[Goldschmidt classification]] elements.
*{{cite book|last1=Faure|first1=Gunter|author-link=Gunter Faure |title=Principles of Isotope Geology|year=1977|publisher=Wiley|location=New York|isbn=9780471256656}}
::A highly cited guide to the use of isotope geochemistry in solving geological problems, and the methods involved. Has been cited more than 3200 times. A second edition was published in 1986.  A third edition, with Teresa M. Mensing, was published in 2005, under the title ''Isotopes: Principles and Applications''.

==Geochronology==
*{{cite journal|first=William |last=Thomson, 1st Baron Kelvin |author-link=William Thomson, 1st Baron Kelvin|title=The age of the Earth as an abode fitted for life |year=1899  |journal=Journal of the Transactions of the Victoria Institute |volume= 31 |pages=11–38}}
::The speech recorded by this volume of Transactions represents the final version of the theory of the [[age of the Earth]] which Thomson has been refining since 1862. In it, he proposed that the age of the Earth was "more than 20 and less than 40 million year old, and probably much nearer 20 than 40".<ref>Dalrymple, G. Brent. The age of the Earth. Stanford University Press, 1994. pp. 14, 43</ref> His analysis was based on the time it would take the Earth to cool from a completely molten state, and his estimate was consistent with a number of other physical estimates from, amongst others, [[George Darwin]], [[Hermann von Helmholtz]], and [[Simon Newcomb]]. This strikingly young age put Thomson in direct conflict with both [[Uniformitarianism|Uniformitarian]] geologists and [[evolutionary biologists]], both of whose theories required much longer spans of time to take effect.<ref>Dalrymple, 1994, p. 14-17.</ref> This paradox of the age of the Earth was resolved only by fuller understanding of the roles of [[convection]] and [[radioactivity]] in the planet's interior in the early 20th century, and it required understanding of [[thermonuclear fusion]] in the Sun developed only in the 1930s to fully explain the stability of the whole solar system over multi-billion year timescales.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Stacey|first1=Frank D.|journal=[[Journal of Geophysical Research]]|volume=105|pages=13155–13158|year=2000|issue=B6|doi=10.1029/2000JB900028|title=Kelvin's age of the Earth paradox revisited|bibcode = 2000JGR...10513155S }}</ref>
*{{Cite journal | last1 = Holmes | first1 = A.| authorlink1 = Arthur Holmes| title = The Association of Lead with Uranium in Rock-Minerals, and Its Application to the Measurement of Geological Time | doi = 10.1098/rspa.1911.0036 | journal = Proceedings of the Royal Society A: Mathematical, Physical and Engineering Sciences | volume = 85 | issue = 578 | page = 248 | year = 1911| url = https://archive.org/details/philtrans07247784 | pmid =  | pmc = |bibcode = 1911RSPSA..85..248H }}
::With this work based on his thesis Holmes describes the first accurate [[Uranium-lead dating|uranium-lead]] [[radiometric dating]] (specifically designed to measure the age of a rock), assigning an age of 370&nbsp;[[Ma (unit)|Ma]] to a [[Devonian]] rock from [[Norway]], improving on the work of [[Bertram Boltwood|Boltwood]] who published nothing more on the subject.

* [[Gerard De Geer|De Geer, G.]] (1912). A geochronology of the last 12000 years. ''Congr. Géol. Int. Stockholm 1910, C.R.'', 241-253.
::In the 1910 International Geological Congress held in Stockholm Gerard De Geer presented to international community his research on [[glacial lake]] [[varve]]s showing that they represented annual layers and were useful in the study of [[deglaciation]].

==Geomorphology==
*{{cite book|first=Louis |last=Agassiz |author-link=Louis Agassiz |title=Études sur les glaciers|year=1840 |publisher=Jent & Gassman |location=Neuchatel|language=French |url=https://books.google.com/?id=fTMAAAAAQAAJ&dq=etudes%20sur%20les%20glaciers&pg=PP1#v=onepage&q=etudes%20sur%20les%20glaciers&f=false}}
::In 1837, Agassiz was the first to scientifically propose that the Earth had been subject to a past ice age.<ref name="evans 1887">E.P. Evans: "[http://rs6.loc.gov/cgi-bin/query/r?ammem/ncps:@field(DOCID+@lit(ABQ7578-0145-13))::|The The Authorship of the Glacial Theory]", ''North American review'' Volume 145, Issue 368, July 1887. Accessed on February 25, 2008.</ref> This book lays out his theories in print. It represents his theories that vast areas of northern Europe had in the past been covered in ice, extending down to the Caspian and Mediterranean seas. The book represents the birth of the fields of [[glaciology]] and glacial [[geomorphology]].<ref>http://academic.emporia.edu/aberjame/histgeol/agassiz/agassiz.htm</ref>

*{{cite report |first=Grove Karl |last=Gilbert |author-link=Grove Karl Gilbert |title=Report on the Geology of the Henry Mountains |publisher=United States Geological Survey Professional Paper |year=1877}}<ref name=Mather/>{{rp|586&ndash;596}}
::G. K. Gilbert lays the groundwork for many ideas in modern geomorphology, such as the diffusive profiles of hillslopes and the formation of [[pediment (geology)|pediment]]s. In addition to its geomorphic significance, it is a description of the last major mountain range to be mapped by Europeans in the contiguous United States.<ref name="BLM">{{cite book|last1=Heath |first1=Steven H. |chapter=A Historical Sketch of the Scientific Exploration of the Region Containing the Grand Staircase-Escalante National Monument |editor-last1=Hill |editor-first1=Linda M. |editor-last2=Koselak|editor-first2=Janine J. |title=Learning from the Land: Grand Staircase-Escalante National Monument Science Symposium Proceedings |publisher=Bureau of Land Management |year=November 4-5, 1997 |page=440 |url=http://www.blm.gov/pgdata/etc/medialib/blm/ut/grand_staircase-escalante/science___research/1997_symposium.Par.22079.File.dat/general01.htm |accessdate=2009-07-05 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121006155725/http://www.blm.gov/pgdata/etc/medialib/blm/ut/grand_staircase-escalante/science___research/1997_symposium.Par.22079.File.dat/general01.htm |archivedate=2012-10-06 |df= }}</ref> (the [[Henry Mountains]] being located in a remote part of [[Utah]]) and a description of its formation as a [[laccolith]].

*{{cite thesis|last=Cvijić|first=Jovan|author-link=Jovan Cvijić|date=1893|title=Das Karstphänomen|language=German|type=PhD}}
::Founding work on [[karst]] geomorphology. The study focus on karst phenomena in the Balcans. [[Albrecht Penck]] was Cvijić's PhD advisor.

*{{cite journal |last=Davis |first=William Morris |author-link=William Morris Davis |date=1899 |title=The geographical cycle |url= |journal=[[The Geographical Journal]] |volume=14 |issue=5 |pages=481–504 |doi= |access-date= }}
::In his 1899 publication William Morris Davis outlines in detail the [[cycle of erosion]] model laying the foundations for the study of [[peneplain]]s, relief development and [[denudation chronology]].

*[[Walery Łoziński|Łozinski, W.]] (1912). Die periglaziale fazies der mechanischen Verwitterung. Comptes Rendus, XI Congres Internationale Geologie, Stockholm 1910.
::In this work Walery Łoziński publishes his presentation at the 1910 International Geological Congress held in Stockholm and establishes [[periglaciation|periglacial geomorphology]] as a new field of study.

*{{cite book |last=Penck |first=Walther |date=1924|title=Die morphologische Analyse |trans-title=Morphological Analysis of Landforms|url= |location= |publisher= |page= |isbn= |author-link=Walther Penck }}
::This work of Walther Penck challenges the cycle of erosion theory of Davis by proposing for the first time a comprehensive alternative model  to landscape evolution. The work was published posthumously by his father [[Albrecht Penck]].<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Orme |first1=Anthony R. |date=2007 |title=The Rise and Fall of the Davisian Cycle of Erosion: Prelude, Fugue, Coda, and Sequel |url= |journal=Physical Geography |volume=28 |issue=6 |pages=474–506 |doi= |access-date= }}</ref> 

*{{cite thesis |last=Hjulström |first=Filip |author-link=Filip Hjulström |date=1935 |title= Studies of the morphological activity of rivers as illustrated by the River Fyris |type=Inaugural Dissertation |chapter= |publisher=Almqvist & Wiksells |docket= |oclc= |url= |access-date=}}
::With this work Filip Hjulström marks a shift towards [[quantitative geomorphology]] and [[process geomorphology]] in Sweden and Europe. The publication is founding stone of the Uppsala School of Physical Geography. It influences the Ph.D. students of Hjulström [[Anders Rapp]], [[Valter Axelsson]], [[Åke Sundborg]] and [[John O. Norrman]].

*{{cite book|last=Bagnold|first=Ralph Alger|author-link=R. A. Bagnold|title=The Physics of Blown Sand and Desert Dunes|publisher=Methuen|place=London|year=1941|pages=265|title-link=The Physics of Blown Sand and Desert Dunes}}
::Laid the foundations of the scientific investigation of the transport of sand by wind.<ref>{{cite journal|doi=10.1038/4571084a|title=In Retrospect: the physics of sand dunes|year=2009|author=Ball, Philip|journal=Nature|volume=457|issue=7233|pages=1084-1085|bibcode = 2009Natur.457.1084B }}</ref>

*{{cite book|first=King |last=Lester Charles |author-link=Lester Charles King |title=South African Scenery|year=1942 |publisher= |location= |url=}}
::In this book King establishes for the first time the major landform of Africa namely the [[African Surface]]. Subsequently the concept would be expanded and modified. King did also argued for [[scarp retreat]] and [[pediplain|pediplanation]] in the book. 

*{{cite book|author-last=Hack|date=1960|author-first=John Tilton|author-link=John Tilton Hack|title=Interpretation of erosional topography in humid temperate regions|publisher=Bobbs-Merrill}}
::Championed the concept of [[dynamic equilibrium]] in geomorphology.<ref>{{cite journal|author-last=Osterkamp|author-first=W.R.|author-last2=Hupp|author-first2=C.R.|title=Memorial to John T. Hack|journal=Memorials|volume=23|pages=59–61}}</ref>

*{{cite journal |last=Rapp |first=A. |author-link=Anders Rapp |date=1960 |title=Recent development of mountain slopes in Kärkevagge and surroundings, northern Scandinavia |url= |journal=[[Geografiska Annaler]] |volume=42 |issue=2 |pages=65–200 |doi= |access-date= }}
::One of the first measurements of [[chemical erosion]] and one of the first quantitative assessments on the relative role of chemical and mechanical weathering in cold climates.

*{{cite journal |last=Stoddart |first=D.R. |author-link=David_Stoddart_(geographer) |date=1969 |title=Climatic geomorphology: Review and reassesment |url= |journal=[[Progress in Geography]] |volume=1 |issue= |pages=159–222 |doi= |access-date= }}
::An article by Stoddart that proved "devastating" for the field of [[climatic geomorphology]] that has been credited for the decline in the popularity in field the late 20th century.<ref name=Thomas2004>{{cite encyclopedia|last=Thomas|first=Michael F.|editor-last=Goudie|editor-first=A.S.|editor-link=Andrew Goudie (geographer)|encyclopedia=Encyclopedia of Geomorphology|title=Tropical geomorphology|year=2004|pages=1063–1069}}</ref><ref name=Goudie2004>{{cite encyclopedia|last=Goudie|first=A.S.|editor-last=Goudie|editor-first=A.S.|author-link=Andrew Goudie (geographer)|encyclopedia=Encyclopedia of Geomorphology|title=Climatic geomorphology|year=2004|pages=162–164}}</ref>

==Geophysics==
*{{cite book|first=Sydney |last=Chapman |author1-link=Sydney Chapman (mathematician) |first2=Julius |last2=Bartels |author2-link=Julius Bartels |url=https://archive.org/details/GeomagnetismVol1 |title=Geomagnetism Volume 1: Geomagnetic and Related Phenomena|publisher=[[Clarendon Press]] |location=Oxford |year=1940 |asin=B002K07MAO|oclc=499431969|others=Volume 6 of The International Series of Monographs on Physics}}
*{{cite book|last=— |url=https://archive.org/details/GeomagnetismVol2_29446 |title=Geomagnetism Volume 2: Analysis of the Data and Physical Theories|publisher=[[Clarendon Press]] |location=Oxford |year=1940 |asin=B0020TCMR8|oclc=458641769}}
::A classic reference on the Earth's magnetic field and related topics in [[meteorology]], [[Solar physics|solar]] and [[Moon|lunar]] physics, the [[Aurora (astronomy)|aurora]], techniques of [[Spherical harmonics|spherical harmonic analysis]] and treatment of periodicities in geophysical data.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.egu.eu/egs/bartels.htm |title=Julius Bartels |author= |accessdate=6 February 2017}}</ref> Its comprehensive summaries made it the standard reference on [[geomagnetism]] and the [[ionosphere]] for at least 2 decades.<ref>{{cite journal |first1=Syun-Ichi |last1=Akasofu |title=The Scientific Legacy of Sydney Chapman |journal=[[Eos (journal)|EOS]] |volume=92 |pages=281&ndash;282 |issue=34 |doi=10.1029/2011EO340001 |year=2011|bibcode = 2011EOSTr..92..281A }}</ref>

