*{{cite book|first=Henry |last=Darcy |author-link=Henry Darcy |title=The Public Fountains of the City of Dijon |publisher=Kendall/Hunt |year=1856 |edition=reprint |isbn=978-0-7575-0540-9 |others=English translation by Patricia Bobeck}}

==Mineralogy and petrology==
*{{cite book|last=Agricola|first=Georgius|author-link=Georgius Agricola |title=De Natura Fossilium|language=Latin |trans-title=On the Nature of Fossils|year=2004|publisher=Dover Publications|location=Mineola, N.Y.|isbn=9780486495910|others= Translated from the first Latin edition of 1546 by Mark Chance Bandy and Jean A. Bandy|title-link=De Natura Fossilium}} 
::Systematic treatise of then known minerals and gemstones as well as other rocks, the first since [[Pliny the Elder|Pliny]]'s ''Natural History''.
*{{cite book|last1=Eskola|first1=P.|author-link=Pentti Eskola|title=The Mineral Facies of Rocks|series=Norsk Geologisk Tidsskrift|date=1920|volume=6|number=1&ndash;2|pages=143&ndash;194}}<ref>{{harvnb| Mather|1967}}</ref>{{rp|151&ndash;159}}
::Established the concept of [[metamorphic facies]].{{Citation needed|date=December 2017}}
*{{cite book|last1=Bowen|first1=N. L.|author-link=Norman L. Bowen|title=The evolution of the igneous rocks|date=1956|publisher=Dover Publications|location=New York|isbn=978-0486603117|edition=Dover}}</ref>
::Originally published in 1928, it applied the principles of chemistry to petrological problems.<ref>{{cite book|editor-last1=Yoder|editor-first1=Hatten Schuyler|title=Evolution of the Igneous Rocks: Fiftieth Anniversary Perspectives|date=2015|publisher=Princeton University Press|isbn=9781400868506}}</ref>
*{{cite book|first1=W. A. |last1=Deer |author1-link=William Alexander Deer|first2=R. A. |last2=Howie|author2-link=Robert A. Howie |first3=J. |last3=Zussman |date=1962 |title=An Introduction to the Rock-forming Minerals|location=London |publisher=Longmans}}
::A condensation of ''Rock-Forming Minerals'' (1962), a 5-volume comprehensive treatise of the physical, chemical, mineralogical, petrological and optical properties of essentially all minerals with nontrivial abundances to be found in terrestrial rocks. Also presents information regarding common origins and associations of each mineral, as well as a practical commentary on how to distinguish each mineral from others which may appear similar.
*{{cite book|last=Wilson|first=M.|author-link=Marjorie Wilson|title=Igneous Petrogenesis|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=UGXuCAAAQBAJ&pg=PP7|date=2012|publisher=Springer Science & Business Media|isbn=978-94-010-9388-0}}
::''Igneous Petrogenesis'' has long been a key reference and advanced introductory book to the science of [[igneous petrology]]. 
*{{cite book|last1=Spear|first1=Frank S.|title=Metamorphic phase equilibria and pressure-temperature-time paths|date=1995|publisher=Mineralogical Soc. of America|location=Washington, DC|isbn=978-0-939950-34-8|edition=2nd}}
::Originally published in 1993; presents the thermodynamic basis for modern, quantitative petrology and systematically reviews metamorphism for most rock types. Popularly also known as the "big blue book".

==Petroleum geology==
*{{cite book|first1=P. R. |last1=Vail |author1-link=Peter Vail|first2=R. M. |last2=Mitchum Jr. |first3=R. G. |last3=Todd |first4=J. M. |last4=Widmier |first5=S. |last5=Thompson |first6=J. B. |last6=Sangree |last7=et. al.|chapter=Seismic stratigraphy and global changes in sea level|editor-last1=Payton|editor-first1=C. E.|title=Seismic Stratigraphy&ndash;Applications to hydrocarbon exploration, AAPG Memoir |volume=26|date=1977|publisher=American Association of Petroleum Geologists|location=Tulsa|pages=49&ndash;205}}
::Original work on seismic [[sequence stratigraphy]].<ref>{{cite book|editor-last1=Roberts|editor-first1=David G.|editor-last2=Bally |editor2-first=A. |title=Principles of regional geology|date=2008|publisher=Elsevier|location=Amsterdam|isbn=9780444530424|page=345|edition=1st}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|editor1-first=Dominic |editor1-last=Emery |editor2-first=Keith |editor2-last=Myers |title=Sequence Stratigraphy|date=2009|publisher=John Wiley & Sons|location=Chichester|isbn=9781444313703|pages=3, 6}}</ref>

==Plate tectonics==
*{{cite book|last1=Pepper|first1=John Henry|author-link=John Henry Pepper |title=The playbook of metals; including personal narratives of visits to coal, lead, copper, and tin mines; with a large number of interesting experiments relating to alchemy and the chemistry of the fifty metallic elements|date=1861|publisher=Routledge, Warne, and Routledge|location=London|url=https://archive.org/details/playbookmetalsi00peppgoog}}
::First book to marshall considerable geological evidence that the [[continents]] are mobile relative to each other around the North Atlantic (mainly). It uses Evan Hopkins booklet (''On the connection of geology with terrestrial magnetism'', 1844), but adapts its data to a [[plutonism|plutonist]] point-of-view.{{citation needed|date=February 2017}}

*{{cite book|last1=Suess|first1=Eduard|author-link=Eduard Suess |title=Das Antlitz der Erde|language=German|trans-title=The Face of the Earth|date=1892|publisher=F. Tempsky|url=https://archive.org/details/dasantlitzderer02suesgoog}}
::First book to show geological evidence that some [[continents]] were linked with each other: Suess set out his belief that across geologic time, the rise and fall of sea levels were mappable across the earth—that is, that the periods of ocean transgression and regression were correlateable from one continent to another. His theory was based upon ''glossopteris'' fern fossils occurring in South America, Africa, and India. His explanation was that the three lands were once connected in a supercontinent, which he named ''Gondwána-Land'' (nowadays usually written [[Gondwana|''Gondwanaland'']]). However Suess mistakenly believed that the oceans flooded the spaces currently between those lands.
::Moreover, Suess expressed views in this book on the connection between Africa and Europe. Eventually, he concluded that the Alps to the north were once at the bottom of an ocean, of which the Mediterranean was a remnant. Suess was not correct in his analysis, which was predicated upon the notion of "contractionism"—the idea that the Earth is cooling down and, therefore, contracting. Nevertheless, he is credited with postulating the earlier existence of the [[Tethys Ocean]], which he named in 1893.
::Suess also introduced in this book the concept of the [[biosphere]], which was later extended by [[Vladimir Vernadsky|Vladimir I. Vernadsky]] in 1926.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Sengor|first1=Thomas Hofman,Gunter Bloschl, Lois Lammerhuber, Werner E. Piller, A.M. Celal|title=The face of the Earth : the legacy of Eduard Suess|date=2014|publisher=European Geosciences Union|location=Germany|isbn=978-3901753695}}</ref>

*{{cite book|last1=Wegener|first1=Alfred|author-link=Alfred Wegener|title=The Origins of Continents and Oceans|date=1915}}
::''Die Entstehung der Kontinente und Ozeane'' was the second book to marshall considerable geological evidence that the [[continents]] are mobile relative to each other on the surface of the Earth. His theory was based upon numerous matches between the [[topography]], [[paleontology]] and past [[climate]] of continents now separated by [[oceans]]. At the time of publication his ideas were not taken seriously by most of the geological community as he could not provide a mechanism for continental motion, but his ideas form the foundations of the modern theory of [[plate tectonics]].

==Sedimentology and stratigraphy==
*{{cite book|first=Nicolaus |last=Steno |author-link=Nicolaus Steno|title=De solido intra solidum naturaliter contento dissertationis prodromus |language=Latin |trans-title=Of Solids Naturally Contained Within Solids |publisher=Firenze |year=1669}}<ref name=Mather/>{{rp|33&ndash;44}}
::First statement of three fundamental laws of geology: the [[law of superposition]], the [[principle of original horizontality]], and the [[cross-cutting relationships|principle of cross-cutting relationships]].<ref name=Cloud>{{harvnb|Cloud|1970}}</ref>{{rp|9}}

*{{cite book|first=Johannes |last=Walther |author-link=Johannes Walther |title=Einleitung in die Geologie als historische Wissenschaft |language=German |trans-title=Introduction to geology as a historical science |publisher=G. Fischer, |location=Jena |year=1893|others=3 volumes}}
*{{cite book|first=R. L. |last=Folk |title=Petrology of Sedimentary Rocks|publisher=Hemphill's |year=1965}}
::The basis for the widely used [[folk classification]] for clastic and carbonate rocks
*{{Cite journal| last3=Halverson | first=P. F. | first2=A. J.| last2=Kaufman| first3=G. P.| first4=D. P.| last=Hoffman | title = A Neoproterozoic Snowball Earth| last4=Schrag| url=http://marine.rutgers.edu/ebme/HistoryEarthSystems/HistEarthSystems_Fall2008/Week6a/Hoffman_et_al_Science_1998.pdf  | journal = [[Science (journal)|Science]]| volume = 281 | issue=5381| pages = 1342–1346 | year = 1998 | doi = 10.1126/science.281.5381.1342 | pmid=9721097|bibcode = 1998Sci...281.1342H }}
::Provided new evidence and revived interest for the [[Precambrian]] world-wide glaciations.

==Structural geology==
*{{cite book|first=John G. |last=Ramsay |author-link=John G. Ramsay |title=Folding and fracturing of rocks|publisher=McGraw–Hill|year=1967}}
::Began a whole school of [[structural geology]] that used the techniques of [[continuum mechanics]] to understand rock structures.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Llana-Funez|first1=S.|last2=Marcos|first2=A.|last3=Bastida|first3=F.|title=Deformation structures and processes within the continental crust: an introduction|journal=Geological Society, London, Special Publications|date=20 March 2014|volume=394|issue=1|pages=1–6|doi=10.1144/SP394.13|bibcode = 2014GSLSP.394....1L }}</ref>

==Paleontology==
*{{cite book|title=Treatise on Invertebrate Paleontology|date=1953–|publisher=Geological Society of America and University of Kansas Press}}
::A definitive multi-authored work of some 50 volumes, written by more than 300 paleontologists, and still a work in progress. It covers every phylum, class, order, family, and genus of fossil and extant (still living) invertebrate animals. [[Raymond C. Moore]] was the founder and first editor.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Selden|first1=P. A.|title=Treatise on Invertebrate Paleontology: A work in progress|journal=PALAIOS|date=26 July 2012|volume=27|issue=7|pages=439–442|doi=10.2110/palo.2012.SO4|bibcode=2012Palai..27..439S}}</ref>

==Seismology==
*{{cite book|last1=Aki|first1=Keiiti|last2=Richards|first2=Paul G.|author1-link=Keiiti Aki|author2-link=Paul G. Richards|title=Quantitative seismology|date=1980|publisher=Freeman|location=San Francisco|isbn=978-0716710585}}
*{{cite journal|last1=Thomsen|first1=Leon|title=Weak elastic anisotropy|journal=Geophysics|date=October 1986|volume=51|issue=10|pages=1954–1966|doi=10.1190/1.1442051|bibcode=1986Geop...51.1954T}}
::Defined a version of elastic anisotropy using transversely isotropic media that could be analyzed through the use of [[Thomsen parameters]]. Most cited paper in the history of geophysics.{{citation needed|date=February 2017}}

==Tectonics==
*{{cite book|last1=Scholz|first1=Christopher H.|title=The mechanics of earthquakes and faulting|date=1994|publisher=Cambridge Univ. Press|location=Cambridge|isbn=9780521407601}}
::An influential review of fault properties, dynamics and growth, how they fail, and how this links to seismology. Highly cited (>2700 citations).{{citation needed|date=February 2017}}
*{{cite journal|last1=McKenzie|first1=D|title=Some remarks on the development of sedimentary basins|journal=Earth and Planetary Science Letters|date=June 1978|volume=40|issue=1|pages=25–32|doi=10.1016/0012-821X(78)90071-7|bibcode=1978E&PSL..40...25M|citeseerx=10.1.1.459.4779}}
::The first paper to lay out the now widely accepted model for formation of sedimentary basins by tectonic stretching of the lithosphere (mechanical thinning), followed by lowering of the basin by the cooling of upwelled, hot asthenosphere at depth below it (isostatic deepening). Highly cited (>2200 citations).{{citation needed|date=February 2017}}

==Volcanology==
*Secundus, Gaius Plinius Caecilius ([[Pliny the Younger]])(97–112). ''[[Plinian eruption#Pliny's description|Letters of Pliny the Younger, Book Six, 16 and 20]].''<ref>{{cite book|last1=Pliny the Younger|title=Complete Letters|date=2006|publisher=Oxford|isbn=9780191604898|pages=142&ndash;146, 150&ndash;151|others=Translated by P. G. Walsh}}</ref>
::Contains the first detailed description of a volcanic eruption in western culture – the eruption of [[Mount Vesuvius]] in what is now known as a [[plinian eruption]] in 79 CE.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Jones|first1=Nicholas F.|title=Pliny the Younger's Vesuvius "Letters" (6.16 and 6.20)|journal=The Classical World|date=2001|volume=95|issue=1|pages=31&ndash;48|doi=10.2307/4352621|jstor=4352621}}</ref>
*{{cite book|editor-last1=Lipman|editor-first1=Peter W.|editor-last2=Mullineaux|editor-first2=Donal R.|title=The 1980 Eruptions of Mount St. Helens, Washington. USGS Professional Paper 1250|date=1981|publisher=United States Geological Survey|location=Washington. D. C.}}
::The 1980 eruption of Mount St. Helens in Washington state, USA, allowed volcanologists to document first hand a large number of volcanic processes which hitherto had been only inferred. It spurred a revitalization of the whole discipline of volcanology. This anthology of papers was amongst the first to present new data gained during the eruption.{{cn|date=February 2017}}

