'''Le Fort's fracture of the ankle''' is a vertical [[Bone fracture|fracture]] of the [[Anatomical terms of location#Anterior and posterior|antero]]-[[Human anatomical terms#Front and back|medial]] part of the [[Anatomical terms of location#Proximal and distal|distal]] [[fibula]] with [[Avulsion fracture|avulsion]] of the [[anterior ligament of the lateral malleolus|anterior tibiofibular ligament]],<ref name="hunter">{{cite journal |author1=Tim B Hunter |author2=Leonard F Peltier |author3=Pamela J Lund |year=2000 |title=Musculoskeletal Eponyms: Who Are Those Guys? |journal=RadioGraphics |volume=20 |pages=829 |url=http://radiographics.rsna.org/content/20/3/819.full.pdf |accessdate=2009-11-13 |doi=10.1148/radiographics.20.3.g00ma20819 |pmid=10835130}}</ref> opposite to a [[Tillaux-Chaput avulsion fracture]]

The injury was described by [[Léon Clément Le Fort]] in 1886.<ref>{{cite journal |last=Le Fort |first=LC |year=1886 |title=Note sur une variete non-decrite de fracture verticale de la malleole externe par arrachement. |trans-title=Note on an undescribed variety of vertical fracture of the lateral malleolus by avulsion. |journal=Bull Gen Ther
|volume=110 |pages=193–199 }}</ref>
